			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Pets no longer poof when owner is invis (on test)<a name="65148"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 30 04 4:16 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Mroog wrote:
<br />
For those who play on test, can you see if this only applies to summoned pets, or does it affect charmed pets as well?</span></blockquote><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Rhyff wrote:
<br />
Cancel the panic, invis still breaks charm on test.</span></blockquote>
<br />
Thank you, Rhyff, for testing this and reporting the results. The whole point of my initial post was to get someone on test to try it out instead of starting a huge panic over unknown facts. Its nice to know that this is indeed for summoned pets only. I regularly group with a shaman and sk and this will allow me to use invis to target for lull in some cases where an eye of zomm would have been needed.
<br />

<br />
As for those who always mention see-invis on a pet, or whether the pet is live, undead, or animal, when talking about this issue: as far as I know, pets poofing on invis has NEVER been about whether or not your pet can &quot;see&quot; you, it is about whether or not OTHER mobs (hostile enemies) can see you while you have a pet. The game designers did not want to allow people to have the advantage of having/using a pet while remaining invis to possible adds/wanderering enemies, that's why any form of invis would remove a pet regardless of pet type and see-invis on pet, because whether or not your pet can see you is irrelevant to the issue.
<br />

<br />
With this new change, they appeared to have reversed their stance on this for summoned pets (likely to allow safer travel for pet classes); maybe they will code it so that you cannot issue /pet attack while invis, or maybe if the pet is on any hate list you will lose invis, to prevent abuse of this new change.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
